<subSubSection pageId="167" pageNumber="770" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="167.[782,1375,1123,1543]" pageId="167" pageNumber="770">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[783,932,1123,1148]" pageId="167" pageNumber="770">Taxonomy.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Thomas, 1910" authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1910" box="[940,1368,1123,1148]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Arvicanthis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="167" pageNumber="770" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="linulus">Arvicanthis linulus Thomas, 1910</taxonomicName>
, 
<materialsCitation box="[784,1305,1154,1188]" pageId="167" pageNumber="770">“Gamon, French Gambia [= Senegal].”</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="167" pageNumber="770" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="167.[782,1375,1123,1543]" pageId="167" pageNumber="770">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Thomas" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[784,1051,1198,1227]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Lemniscomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="167" pageNumber="770" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="linulus">Lemniscomys linulus</taxonomicName>
was previously treated as a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName box="[1057,1196,1242,1267]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Lemniscomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="167" pageNumber="770" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="griselda">L. griselda</taxonomicName>
, but was reinstated as a full species by E. Van der Straeten in 1980. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="167" pageNumber="770" type="distribution">
<caption inLine="true" pageId="167" pageNumber="770" startId="167.[782,955,1351,1385]" targetBox="[168,759,1125,1538]" targetPageId="167">
<paragraph blockId="167.[782,1375,1123,1543]" pageId="167" pageNumber="770">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[782,959,1351,1385]" pageId="167" pageNumber="770">Distribution.</emphasis>
W Africa W of the Dahomey Gap, including 
<taxonomicName box="[1000,1110,1395,1424]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Solanecio" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="167" pageNumber="770" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="senegal">Senegal</taxonomicName>
, Mali, Guinea, and Ivory Coast.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="167" pageNumber="770" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="167.[782,1375,1123,1543]" pageId="167" pageNumber="770">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[782,1025,1470,1504]" pageId="167" pageNumber="770">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head—body 93-126 mm, tail 95-135 mm, ear 15-18 mm, hindfoot
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="167.[167,1375,1549,2015]" pageId="167" pageNumber="770">
23-28 mm; weight 37-41 g. The 
<taxonomicName authority="Striped Grass Mouse" authorityName="Striped Grass Mouse" box="[624,1025,1549,1583]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Solanecio" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="167" pageNumber="770" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="senegal">Senegal Striped Grass Mouse</taxonomicName>
has fur buffy gray above, contrasting with pure white below, with clear black mid-dorsal stripe and many indistinct lateral stripes of very small pale spots. Tail is long (c.100-105% of head-body length), dark brown above, ocherous laterally, and buff below. Forefeet and hindfeet are buffcolored. Females have 2+2 = 4 pairs of nipples.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
